        "entry_id": "668ad1b8-9355-4e3c-9b3e-47bc9cfe75f1",
        "essay_identifier": "Tell a story from your life, describing an experience that either demonstrates your character or hel",
        "raw_text": "Answer any one of the questions from the dropdown.\nPlease use the box below to type in your answer.\nFew years back, a seemingly biased competition changed my outlook and helped me comprehend the nature of my results.My friend and I\nwere selected to represent our school in an inter-school STEM contest. Our goal was to use STEM skills to create solutions to real-world\nissues. We decided to work on a tra\ufb03c control system that could seamlessly generate challan and redirect tra\ufb03c on the \ufb02y to make way for\nany emergency service vehicle. It was a solid plan, and I think we did a great job realizing our project.The day of the event had \ufb01nally arrived,\nand we felt pretty good about our chances. There were many unique and creative ideas with a ton of thought and work put in, but there is\none project that I can still remember vividly. One team had made a line-follower robot that could be used to transport a few \ufb01les around the\nschool. It was clearly from some pre-made robotics kit. The judges soon came around to inspect our project. I think we did a decent job of\nconveying our idea. I was able to explain all of my points and answer their question su\ufb03ciently. The demo went without any hiccups. We\ndidn\\'t win 1st or 2nd place, which was understandable; they were clearly better than us, but 3rd place was given to the line-follower robot!I\nwas absolutely livid. I knew we weren\\'t the best, but this clearly seemed like the wrong decision. It felt like a blatant miscarriage of justice. I\nwas consumed by this feeling of being wronged, \ufb01xating on that moment and blaming the judges. Of course, this wasn\\'t a healthy line of\nthought, and it was only hurting me. There was no use in focusing on something I couldn\\'t change. The amount of work I put in is all that I\nhave control over; it is the only way I can change my performance. My e\ufb00ort is the only thing that determines my results.\u201cBetween stimulus\nand response, there is a space. In that space, is our power to choose our response. In our response lies our growth and our freedom.\u201d \u2015\nViktor E. Frankl And I choose to attribute my successes and failures to my e\ufb00orts.\n",
        "word_count": 387,
        "character_count": 2131,
        "placeholder_flag": false,
